A "perfect" tree

A "perfect" tree

More likely

Single tree

  • Looks informative
  • very susceptible to small changes in the data
  • even to a single data point

Use multiple trees

  • simulate large number of subsets of the data
  • look for frequently occurring features

Example: predicting insect trap catch

  • Numerous possible influences

  • orchard practices

  • landscape parameters

  • weather/climate

  • Approach is to divide data into training and testing sections

    • build model using large number of samples; observe how often/much parameters influence the dependant variable
    • test the model's ability to predict data held out of model

Conclusion

  • little difference which regression tree is used

  • if aim is to predict low occurrence, choices are narrower

  • use other algorithms such as Support Vector Machines and compare results

  • No fixed rule which is the most useful
